file=Cybersecurity/keyring/operational/tool/keyring-tool-requirements.md · k—t:keyring — Tool Requirements=**Specifies needs; does not grant them.** Fleet Charter Rails 1–2 (registered, least privilege); every external call plan-locked + sandboxed.\n · tb=\| Skill \| Needs \| Why \| · tb=\|---\|---\|---\| · tb=\| identity-lifecycle \| READ of IdP/account state; file write (access matrix / JML records) \| design + detect JML gaps \| · tb=\| access-reviews \| READ of entitlements; script execution (access_review.py — stdlib); file write (review diffs) \| recertification diff \| · tb=\| privileged-access-management \| READ of privileged-account inventory + logs \| minimize + monitor \| · tb=\| secrets-governance \| READ of secret-scanning results; file write (secrets policy/inventory) \| vault/rotation discipline \| · en/:Explicit non-needs / hard prohibition (the security-inversion)=- **NO write/execute access to the IdP, PAM, or vault** — keyring never provisions, revokes, or rotates; the operator/IdP/PAM/vault executes.\n- **No key-holding** — keyring designs access and detects gaps; it holds no credentials.\n- **No standing privilege of its own** — the agent that governs privilege must not accumulate it.\n · n:=- keyring is read-and-recommend by design; its power is the diff and the policy, not the action.\n- IdP/PAM/vault are the executors, configured per business; keyring's `access_review.py` is stdlib-only (no vendor dependency).\n